16	Live	\N	8	[\nlive/cascade-falls-1.jpg,\nlive/cascade-falls-2.jpg,\nlive/cascade-falls-3.jpg,\nlive/cascade-lake-1.jpg,\nlive/cascade-lake-2.jpg,\nlive/mt-constitution-1.jpg,\nlive/mt-constitution-2.jpg,\nlive/mt-constitution-3.jpg,\nlive/mt-baker.jpg,\nlive/fishing.jpg,\nlive/pontoon-boating.jpg,\nlive/snow-1.jpg,\nlive/snow-2.jpg,\nlive/snow-3.jpg,\nlive/sunset-north-beach.jpg,\nlive/sunset-rosario.jpg,\nlive/grace.jpg,\nlive/trawler.jpg\n]	\N	{\n    "slide_show_type": "subject",\n    "row_style": "text-left",\n    "text_classes": "col-lg-4",\n    "image_classes": "col-lg-8 mb-3",\n    "row_classes": "expandableOrcasRows"\n}	<title>\n  Waterfalls\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    This is cascade falls. It empties into Cascade Lake. It's just a short hike (less that 1/2 mile) from the parking lot in Moran State Park.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Waterfalls\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    Another view of the falls looking up from the bottom.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Waterfalls\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    Finally, for perspective, this is a picture of the falls with Paul's daughter and her boyfriend Ryan.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Lakes\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    Orcas Island has several lakes: Cascade Lake, Mountain Lake, Twin Lakes, Summit Lake, and Killebrew Lake amount others.\n    Paul lives next to Moran State Park and is only about 1/2 mile from Cascade Lake.\n    In the summer Paul loves to swim in the lake in summer (it's too cold in the winter).\n    This is a picture of cascade lake taken from the lagoon. You can see the bridge in the background.\n    Everyone loves to jump off the bridge into the lake.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Lakes\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    This is another picture of Cascade Lake.\n    It's taken from a cliff that people jump off of into the lake.\n    But be careful it's a long drop.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Mt. Constitution\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    As was mentioned above, Mt. Constitution is about 2,000 feet tall. This is the view west from about half way up.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Mt. Constitution\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    This is the view from the top of Mt. Constitution facing north. You can see Canada off in the distance.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Mt. Constitution\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    This is the view from the top of Mt. Constitution facing west. Mt baker in in the view. It's a popular ski resort\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Mt. Constitution\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    While not take from Mt. Constitution, this is another view of Mt. Baker.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Activities\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    There is a lot to do on orcas: fishing, kayaking, boating, cycling, and beach combing.\n    This is Paul's daughter Joy helping her daughter to fish.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Activities\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    While you can sail or powerboat in the waters around Orcas Island, you can also boat on some of the lakes.\n    This is Paul's son Jonathan 0n a pontoon boat on Cascade Lake.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Snow\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    Orcas does get snow in the winter. Sometimes it can be up to 18"-24" but it tends to melt in the low-lands rather quickly.\n    It usually is gone in less than a week.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Snow\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    This the front of Paul's house during a snow storm.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Snow\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    This another shot of the front of Paul's house.\n    When it does snow, it nearly impossible to get out of the driveway. It a good thing Paul works remotely.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Sunsets\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    While Orcas doesn't have as colorful sunsets as Southern California (where Paul grew up), they are still very beautiful.\n    This was taken from North Beach, the north end of Orcas Island.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Sunsets\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    This was a sunset taken from Rosario resort. Paul lives less than a quarter mile above Rosario resort.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Boating\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    For several years, Paul had a motor-yacht called Grace.\n    Unfortunately it sank but we have fond memories of boating around Orcas and even up into Canada.\n    This is a picture of Grace up in Princess Louise Inlet in Canada. It's a beautiful place with no one around.\n    If you are boating in the northern part of Washington state, Paul, highly recommends visiting princess, Louisa Inlet.\n    If you do visit, make sure to stop at Camp Malibu and have an ice cream sundae.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Boating\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    As mentioned before, pleasure boating is quite common on Orcas, but there are also commercial crab fisherman.\n  </p>\n</section>	2024-11-16 08:43:01.457896	2024-11-29 18:39:53.32956	
19	Live	\N	11	[\nlive/orca-1.jpg,\nlive/orca-2.jpg,\nlive/orcas-1.jpg,\nlive/orcas-2.jpg,\nlive/seals.jpg,\nlive/otters.jpg,\nlive/little-crab.jpg,\ncooking/crabs.jpg,\nlive/clam.jpg,\nlive/eagle-1.jpg,\nlive/eagle-2.jpg,\nlive/eagle-3.jpg,\nlive/eagle-4.jpg,\nlive/eagle-5.jpg,\nlive/heron.jpg\n]\n	\N	{\n    "slide_show_type": "subject",\n    "row_style": "text-left",\n    "text_classes": "col-lg-4",\n    "image_classes": "col-lg-8 mb-3",\n    "row_classes": "expandableWildLifeRows"\n}	<title>\n  Orcas\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    While the "whale" orca has nothing to do with the name of the island, there are lots of orcas around Orcas Island.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Orcas\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    You can see whales on almost every trip out with whale watching boats.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Orcas\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    Orcas Island is home to the J and K pods of "killer whales".\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Orcas\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    Perhaps this shouldn't be said publicly but Paul and an unwanted encounter with some Orcas.\n    As was mentioned, previously, Paul had a motor-yacht called Grace. Paul and his family love to go out whale watching.\n    One day, Paul was observing the required distance from the Orcas, paralleling them, so as not to disturb them.\n    Unbeknownst to Paul, the whales changed their course and decided to come up from behind him.\n    They surfaced very close to the front of his boat.\n    Paul immediately put the engines in reverse so as not to have an incident with the whales but they did scare him.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Seals\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    The area around Orcas Island is home to both seals and sea lions.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Otters\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    Orcas has both river and sea otters.\n    Paul had a wonderful experience with them once.\n    As mentioned, Paul likes to swim in Cascade Lake in the summer.\n    At the end of one swim Paul was coming back while swimming.\n    As he got near the end of the swim he saw some heads in the water.\n    At first, he thought they were children.\n    As he got closer he thought "those don't look right".\n    He then realized he was swimming with otters.\n    It was an amazing experience.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Other Sea Life\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    There is a lot of other sea life around Orcas Island.\n    There are salmon (there's even a salmon hatchery on Orcas), clams, muscles, oysters, crabs, and lots of little fish.\n    Orcas is home to one of the largest beds of sand dollars.\n    Beach combing on Orcas is a fun past time. You'll see lots of little fish and crabs as you weighed into the shallow bays.\n    This is a picture of a tiny crab. You have to look carefully. It's fairly small. It's in the center of the picture.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Other Sea Life\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    Not to offend any viewers who are vegetarian or vegan, the crabs on the island are delicious.\n    One of Paul's favorite past times, when he had his boat, was to go out and drop crab pots, then go explore.\n    After he was done exploring, Paul and his family would pull up the crab pots and boil the crabs on the boat, then eat them.\n    They were delicious.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Other Sea Life\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    You can see clams when you are beach combing, just look for the hole or the spurts of water.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Eagles\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    Orcas is home to both Bald and Golden Eagle, however you are more likley to see a Bald Eagle that a Golden Eagle.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Eagles\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    The eagles tend to rest on dead tress or tree branches.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Eagles\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    Here's an eagle resting on a branch in the forest.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Eagles\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    There is a dead tree near Paul's house and he can often see them from his back deck.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Eagles\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    Eagles do fish here is one near the water waiting for lunch.\n  </p>\n</section>\n<title>\n  Herons\n</title>\n<section>\n  <p>\n    Orcas is home to Blue Herons. While they are lovely birds but they can be a pest.\n    Here is one waiting to make a meal out of the fish in Paul's pond.\n  </p>\n</section>	2024-11-16 08:43:01.457896	2024-11-29 18:39:53.33997	
